tables.name: dim_address
tables.description: This dimension table contains the billing and shipping addresses of customers. You can join this table with the sales table to generate lists of the billing and shipping addresses. Customers can enter their addresses more than once, so the same address can appear in more than one row in this table. This table contains one row per customer address.

columns.name: address_id
columns.description: Unique identifier for the address.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: The ID of the store. This column is a foreign key reference to the shop_id column in the dim_shop table.

columns.name: first_name
columns.description: First name of the customer.

columns.name: last_name
columns.description: Last name of the customer.

columns.name: address1
columns.description: The first address line. For example, 150 Elgin St.

columns.name: address2
columns.description: The second address line. For example, Suite 800.

columns.name: company
columns.description: The name of the customer's business, if one exists.

columns.name: city
columns.description: The name of the city. For example, Palo Alto.

columns.name: region
columns.description: The name of the region, such as a province or state, where the customer is located. For example, Ontario or New York. This column is the same as CustomerAddress.province in the Admin API.

columns.name: zip
columns.description: The ZIP or postal code. For example, 90210.

columns.name: country
columns.description: The full name of the country. For example, Canada.

columns.name: phone
columns.description: The phone number of the customer.

tables.name: dim_api_client
tables.description: This dimension table contains a row for each channel or app that your customers use to create orders. Some examples of these include Facebook and Online Store. You can join this table with the sales table to measure channel performance.

columns.name: api_client_id
columns.description: ID of the API client that called the Shopify API. For example, the ID for the online store is 580111.

columns.name: title
columns.description: Full name of the app or channel. For example, Point of Sale, Online Store.

tables.name: dim_customer
tables.description: The dimension table contains data about your customers. The customers table contains one row per customer. It includes historical metrics (such as the total amount that each customer has spent in your store) as well as forward-looking metrics (such as the predicted number of days between future orders and the expected order value in the next 30 days). This table also includes columns that segment customers into various categories (such as new, returning, promising, at risk, dormant, and loyal), which you can use to target marketing activities.

columns.name: customer_id
columns.description: The ID of the customer. This is the primary key column for this table.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: The ID of the store. This column is a foreign key reference to the shop_id column in the dim_shop table.

columns.name: average_order_size
columns.description: The average amount of money that the customer spends on orders from the store. The value is formatted in the store's currency and it is calculated using the following formula: total_order_value / total_order_count.

columns.name: total_order_count
columns.description: The total number of orders that the customer has made from this store across their lifetime.

columns.name: total_order_value
columns.description: The total amount of money that the customer has spent on orders from the store across their lifetime. The value is formatted in the store's currency.

columns.name: first_order_date
columns.description: The date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the customer placed their first order. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: last_order_date
columns.description: The date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the customer placed their most recent order. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: rank
columns.description: A numeric ranking of the customer's lifetime value for the store relative to all customers.

columns.name: new
columns.description: Returns true if the customer made their first order in the last 30 days. Otherwise returns false.

columns.name: returning
columns.description: Returns true when the customer has made more than one order. Returns false when the customer has made one order only. Returns Null when the customer exists in Shopify, but they have not made any orders. For example, this column can be null because the customer provided their contact information and then abandoned the checkout. Customers can also be created manually in the Shopify admin and by apps that use the Admin API.

columns.name: loyal
columns.description: Returns true when the customer has a high probability of returning, and has placed more orders than the average customer. Otherwise returns false.

columns.name: at_risk
columns.description: Returns true for repeat customers, who have a medium probability of returning and have not placed an order in a while. Otherwise returns false.

columns.name: dormant
columns.description: Returns true when the customer has a very low probability of returning to make another purchase. Otherwise returns false.

columns.name: promising
columns.description: Returns true when the customer has a high probability of returning and becoming a loyal customer. Otherwise returns false.

columns.name: predicted_average_number_of_days_between_orders
columns.description: The predicated number of days between future orders.

columns.name: expected_purchase_value_in_next_30_days
columns.description: The total purchase amount of the orders that the customer is expected to make in the next 30 days. The value is formatted in the store's currency.

columns.name: first_name
columns.description: The first name of the customer.

columns.name: last_name
columns.description: The last name of the customer.

columns.name: city
columns.description: The city from the customer's billing address. For example, Topeka.

columns.name: region
columns.description: The name of the region, such as the province or state, from the customer's billing address. For example, Alberta, Florida. This column is the same as CustomerAddress.province in the Admin API.

columns.name: country
columns.description: The country from the customer's billing address. For example, United States.

columns.name: email
columns.description: The email of the customer.

columns.name: phone
columns.description: The phone number of the customer.

columns.name: verified_email
columns.description: Returns true when the customer's email has been verified. Otherwise returns false.

columns.name: created_at
columns.description: The date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the customer was added to the store. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2018-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: accepts_marketing
columns.description: Returns true when the customer has agreed to accept marketing. Otherwise returns false.

tables.name: dim_location
tables.description: The dimension table contains metrics about your Shopify POS. This table contains one row per Shopify POS location. You can use this table to generate a list of the Shopify POS locations or you can join the table with the sales table to measure sales performance.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: The ID of the store. This column is a foreign key reference to the shop_id column in the dim_shop table.

columns.name: name
columns.description: Name of the POS location as provided by the merchant. For example, 150 Elgin Street or Downtown Boutique.

tables.name: dim_product
tables.description: This dimension table contains information about each of the products in your store. This table contains one row per product. This table reflects the current state of products in your Shopify admin.

columns.name: product_id
columns.description: Unique identifier for the product. This column is the primary key for this table.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: ID of the store. This column is a foreign key reference to the shop_id column in the dim_shop table.

columns.name: title
columns.description: Name of the product.

columns.name: vendor
columns.description: Name of the manufacturer, wholesaler, or other vendor of the product.

columns.name: created_at
columns.description: Date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the product was added to the store. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: deleted_at
columns.description: Date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the product was deleted. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

tables.name: dim_product_variant
tables.description: This dimension table contains current information about each of the product variants in your store. This table contains one row per product variant.

columns.name: product_variant_id
columns.description: The ID of the product variant. This column is the primary key for this table.

columns.name: product_id
columns.description: The ID of the product. This column is a foreign key reference to the product_id column in dim_product table.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: The ID of the store. This column is a foreign key reference to the shop_id column in the dim_shop table.

columns.name: title
columns.description: The title of the product variant.

columns.name: barcode
columns.description: The Barcode, UPC, or ISBN number of the product variant.

columns.name: sku
columns.description: The SKU of the product variant.

columns.name: price
columns.description: The price of the product variant, in your store's currency.

columns.name: grams
columns.description: Number of grams that the product variant weighs.

columns.name: created_at
columns.description: The date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the product variant was added to the store. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: deleted_at
columns.description: The date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the product variant was deleted. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

tables.name: dim_shop
tables.description: This dimension table contains online shop information. This table contains one shop per row.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: Unique identifier for the store. This column is the primary key for this table.

columns.name: name
columns.description: Name of your store.

columns.name: domain
columns.description: Primary domain specified for your online store. Your primary domain is the one that your customers and search engines see. For example, www.mycompany.com.

tables.name: dim_staff
tables.description: This dimension table contains information about the staff accounts in the store. It contains one row per staff account. Use this table to generate a list of your staff accounts, or join it with the sales, API clients and locations tables to analyze staff performance at Shopify POS locations.

columns.name: user_id
columns.description: Unique identifier for the user of your Shopify POS or your Shopify admin.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: The ID of the store. This column is a foreign key reference to the shop_id column in the dim_shop table.

columns.name: first_name
columns.description: First name of the staff member.

columns.name: last_name
columns.description: Last name of the staff member.

columns.name: email
columns.description: Email address of the staff member.

tables.name: fact_line_item
tables.description: The fact table contains information about the line items in orders. Each row in the table is a line item in an order. It contains product and product variant details as they were at the time of the order. This table does not include information about returns. Join this table with the TODO fact_sales table to get the details of the product on the day it was sold. This data will match what appears on the order in your Shopify admin as well as the in the Sales reports.

columns.name: line_item_id
columns.description: ID of the line item. This column is the primary key for the this table.

columns.name: order_id
columns.description: ID of the order. This column is a foreign key reference to the orders_id column in the fact_order table.

columns.name: product_id
columns.description: ID of the product ordered, unless the line item is for shipping costs (you can add custom items using a draft order). This column is a foreign key reference to the product_id column in the dim_product table.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: ID of the store. This column is a foreign key reference to the shop_id column in the dim_shop table.

columns.name: name
columns.description: Name of the line item. This name combines the product title and the variant title into the following format: product-title - variant-title. If there is no variant title, then the format is product-title. This column is the same as order.line_items.name"in the Admin API.

columns.name: product_title
columns.description: Name of the product ordered. This column is the same as order.line_items.title in the Admin API.

columns.name: price
columns.description: Price of the product variant.

columns.name: quantity
columns.description: Number of product variant items ordered in the line item.

columns.name: requires_shipping
columns.description: Whether the product variant requires fulfillment (shipping). For example, online gift cards don't require shipping.

columns.name: taxable
columns.description: Whether taxes are charged for the product variant, otherwise contains 0. For example, when the line item is a gift card, taxes are not charged.

columns.name: gift_card
columns.description: Whether the product variant is a gift card.

columns.name: grams
columns.description: Weight of a single unit of the product variant. Contains 0 when the product variant is a gift card.

columns.name: product_vendor
columns.description: Name of the manufacturer, wholesaler, or other vendor of the product.

columns.name: fulfillable_quantity
columns.description: Number of product variant items in the line item that require fulfillment. Some product variants, such as gift cards and digital products, do not need to be fulfilled.

columns.name: fulfillment_service
columns.description: Name of the fulfillment service provider that fulfilled (shipped) the variant ordered. Contains manual when there is no fulfillment service specified for the variant.

tables.name: fact_order
tables.description: The orders table contains information about each order in your store. Although this table is good for generating order lists and joining with the dim_customer, use the sales table instead for computing financial or other metrics.

columns.name: order_id
columns.description: Unique numeric identifier for the order across Shopify stores. In your Shopify admin, this ID is used internally. Most merchants are familiar with the other ID that appears on orders in the Shopify admin. This ID can be found in the Name column.

columns.name: api_client_id
columns.description: The ID of the API client that called the Shopify API. This column is a foreign key reference to the api_client_id column in the dim_api_client table.

columns.name: customer_id
columns.description: The ID of the customer. This column is a foreign key reference to the customer_id column in the dim_customer table.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: The ID of the store. This column is a foreign key reference to the shop_id column in the dim_shop table.

columns.name: user_id
columns.description: The ID of the staff member who created the order. This column is a foreign key reference to the ID in the dim_staff table. This column applies to Shopify POS orders and to orders that were converted from draft orders.

columns.name: name
columns.description: The identifier of the order that the merchant and customer sees. This is the ID that appears on the order in the Shopify admin. For example, #1001. By default, this identifier is unique to one store. If you have multiple stores, then use the order_id column to guarantee uniqueness across multiple stores.

columns.name: total_price
columns.description: The total price of the order, including shipping and taxes. This column includes gift card sales, but does not include returns. This value may not be accurate for API-imported orders. Do not use this column for financial calculations. Instead, use the total_price column in the sales table.

columns.name: discount_code
columns.description: The discount code that was applied to the order.

columns.name: processed_at
columns.description: The date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the order was created. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: canceled_at
columns.description: If the order was canceled, then this column contains the date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the order was canceled. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: deleted_at
columns.description: If the order was deleted, then this column contains the date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the order was deleted. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: test
columns.description: True when the order is a test order, False otherwise.

tables.name: fact_sale
tables.description: The fact table captures the value of products sold or returned, as well as the values of other charges such as taxes and shipping costs. The sales table contains one row per order line item, one row per returned line item, and one row per shipping charge. Use this table when you need financial metrics.

columns.name: sale_id
columns.description: ID of the sale row. This column is the primary key for this table.

columns.name: billing_address_id
columns.description: ID of the billing address of the customer. This column is a foreign key reference to the address_id column in the dim_address table.

columns.name: api_client_id
columns.description: ID of the API client from which the adjustment was made. This column is a foreign key reference to the ID of the API client in the dim_api_client table.

columns.name: customer_id
columns.description: ID of the customer. This column is a foreign key reference to the customer_id column in the dim_customer table.

columns.name: line_item_id
columns.description: ID of the line item. This column is a foreign key reference to line_item_id column in the fact_line_item table. When the row describes a shipping charge, there is no line_item_id value.

columns.name: location_id
columns.description: ID of the Shopify POS location. This column is a foreign key reference to the location_id column in the dim_location table. When the order is not a POS order, then there is no location ID.

columns.name: order_id
columns.description: ID of the order. This column is a foreign key reference to order_id column in the fact_order table.

columns.name: product_id
columns.description: ID of the product sold or returned. This column is a foreign key reference to the product_id column in the dim_product table. When the line item describes a shipping charge, then there is no product ID.

columns.name: product_variant_id
columns.description: ID of the product variant sold or returned. This column is a foreign key reference to the product_variant_id column in the dim_product_variant table. When the row describes a shipping charge, then there is no product variant ID.

columns.name: shipping_address_id
columns.description: ID of the shipping address of the customer who made the order. This column is a foreign key reference to the address_id column in the dim_address table. Some sales, such as those made using Shopify POS, do not have a customer's shipping address associated with them.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: ID of your store. This column is a foreign key reference to the shop_id column in the dim_shop table.

columns.name: user_id
columns.description: ID of the staff member who is associated with the sale. This column is a foreign key reference to the user_id column in the dim_staff table. Not all sales have a staff member associated with them.

columns.name: gross_sales
columns.description: Price of the product purchased multiplied by the quantity ordered. This value is formatted in the currency of your store. If the product purchased is a gift card, then 0 is returned because gift cards are not included in gross sales calculations. The gross sales amount also does not include any discounts, returns, taxes or shipping charges. The gross_sales column is calculated using the following formula: product (excluding gift cards) price x quantity (before taxes, shipping, discounts, and returns). Canceled, pending, and unpaid orders will have a value for this column, but test and deleted orders will not.

columns.name: net_sales
columns.description: Net sales of the line item. The value of the line item's gross sales minus any discounts minus the value of any returned items. Net sales does not include taxes or shipping costs, or the sale of gift cards. If the line item contains gift cards, then the field contains 0. Net sales is calculated by using the following formula: gross_sales - discounts - returns.

columns.name: total_sales
columns.description: Total sales of the line item. This value does not include gift cards. Total sales is calculated using the following formula: net_sales + shipping + taxes.

columns.name: returns
columns.description: Value of the products returned by the customer regardless of the amount that the merchant actually receives from the customer. This value is usually a negative number, but it can also be zero (for example, if the item being returned was a free gift with purchase). Taxes and shipping charges are not included. The returns amount is calculated by using the following formula: 0 - (product variant price * quantity) + discounts.

columns.name: discounts
columns.description: Total amount discounted from the line item. The discounts column contains the sum of any line item discounts plus the line item's portion of any order-level discount. The value of the discount is either negative or zero. The discounts column is calculated using the following formula: line item discount + order level discount share.

columns.name: shipping
columns.description: When the line item is for a shipping charge, this column contains the amount charged for shipping the order or the amount of the shipping charge that is refunded when an item is returned. This value is positive for a shipping charge, and negative for the value returned. Any applicable taxes charged for shipping costs are recorded in the Taxes column. This column is calculated using the following formula: shipping charge or refund - shipping discount..

columns.name: taxes
columns.description: The amount of taxes charged or returned for the line item. This value will be positive for a sale and negative for a return. Tax on an order is split proportionally amongst the line items to which it applies. Gift cards are not taxed. If multiple taxes are applied (for example, State and City sales taxes), then this column contains the sum of those tax amounts. This column can include taxes charged on shipping, if they are applicable.

columns.name: gift_card_discounts
columns.description: Total amount discounted from gift card sales. For example, if a $50 gift card is sold at a $10 discount for $40, then this column will contain $10.

columns.name: gift_card_gross_sales
columns.description: Total face value of gift cards sold. For example, a $50 gift card is sold at a $10 discount for $40. In this example, the gift_card_gross_sales column will contain $50. Use this column to measure the increase in liabilities due to gift cards being issued (even though this value will not balance against the actual payments that you receive).

columns.name: gift_cards_issued
columns.description: Net amount that the gift cards sold for, after discounts. For example, for a $50 gift card sold at a $10 discount for $40, this column will contain $40. Use this column to balance against the payments that you receive.

columns.name: quantity
columns.description: Quantity of the items sold or returned. This value will be negative for returns and zero for line items that contain shipping charges.

columns.name: currency
columns.description: Three-letter ISO currency code of the payment. For example, USD is the code for United States Dollar. This is the currency of the store at the time of the order.

columns.name: is_deleted
columns.description: Contains 1 when the sale's order was deleted, otherwise contains 0.

columns.name: test
columns.description: Whether the sale is a test order. Returns True when the sale is a test sale. See Test orders.

columns.name: happened_at
columns.description: Date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the order was created for a sale or when the order was returned.

tables.name: fact_session
tables.description: This fact table contains information about the visitors to your online store. This table has one row per session, where one session can contain many page views. If you use Urchin Traffic Module (UTM) parameters in marketing campaigns, then you can use this table to track how many customers they direct to your store.

columns.name: derived_session_token
columns.description: The ID of the visitor session. This column is the primary key for the table.

columns.name: shop_id
columns.description: The ID of the store. This column is a foreign key reference to the shop_id column in the dim_shop table.

columns.name: session_duration
columns.description: The time that the visitor spent in your store during the session. This value is the sum of the time spent on each page view (except for the last page viewed) during the session. The maximum value is 1800 seconds (30 minutes).

columns.name: count_of_pageviews
columns.description: The number of pages viewed during the session.

columns.name: session_started_at
columns.description: The date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when this visitor session begins. It is the timestamp when the visitor first visits the store during this session. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: session_token
columns.description: The ID of the session token that is created by the browser. A session token expires after 30 minutes of inactivity.

columns.name: user_token
columns.description: The unique token assigned to the user. A user token expires after 2 years of inactivity.

columns.name: landing_page_url
columns.description: The full URL of the first page visited during the session. For example, https://www.myshop.com/products/cool-tshirt?utm_source=Shop&utm_medium=....

columns.name: exit_page_path
columns.description: The path portion of the URL of the last page that the visitor visited during the session. This field is the same as exit_page_url except that it doesn’t contain the name of the store or any parameters. For example, /products/cool-tshirt.

columns.name: exit_page_url
columns.description: The full URL of the last page that the visitor visited during the session. For example, https://www.myshop.com/products/cool-tshirt?utm_source=Shop&utm_medium=....

columns.name: referrer_tld
columns.description: The top-level domain of the referring website. For example, if the hostname is www.facebook.com, then the referrer_tld is com.

columns.name: ua_browser
columns.description: The name of the browser that the visitor used. For example, Mobile Safari, Chrome.

columns.name: ua_raw
columns.description: The string that identifies the user agent of the user. User agent shows data about the operating system and device that a visitor uses to browse your store.

columns.name: count_of_orders_completed
columns.description: The number of orders created during the session.

columns.name: completed_first_order_at
columns.description: The date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the visitor completes their first order during this session. Contains NULL if the visitor never completes an order during this session. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: hit_first_checkout_at
columns.description: The date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the visitor first visits the checkout page during this session. Contains NULL if the visitor never visits the checkout page during the session. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: started_first_checkout_at
columns.description: The date (ISO 8601) and time (UTC) when the visitor first starts entering their information into the checkout fields. Contains NULL if the visitor never enters their information during the session. The format is YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss (for example, 2016-02-05 17:04:01).

columns.name: count_of_cart_additions
columns.description: The number of items added to the cart during the session. For example, if a customer adds 5 t-shirts and 1 lipstick to their cart, and then removes one of the t-shirts, then the value in this column is 6.

columns.name: count_of_distinct_products_added_to_cart
columns.description: The number of distinct products added to the cart during the session. For example, if a customer adds 5 t-shirts and 1 lipstick are added to the cart, then the value in this column is 2.

columns.name: count_of_distinct_product_variants_added_to_cart
columns.description: The number of distinct product variants added to the cart during the session. For example, if a customer adds 2 small and 3 large t-shirts and 1 lipstick to the cart, then the value in this column is 3.

columns.name: had_error
columns.description: True when an an error appears during the checkout that is not a payment error, False otherwise.

columns.name: had_payment_error
columns.description: True when a payment error occurs during the checkout, False otherwise.

columns.name: had_out_of_stock_warning
columns.description: True when an out-of-stock warning appears on the checkout page, False otherwise.

columns.name: had_credit_card_info_error
columns.description: True when a payment error occurs because of a credit card error, False otherwise.

columns.name: had_discount
columns.description: True when a checkout error occurs because of a discount error, False otherwise.

columns.name: had_free_shipping
columns.description: True when the order has no shipping cost, False otherwise.

columns.name: location_city
columns.description: The name of the city where the visitor is located. For example, Topeka.

columns.name: location_region
columns.description: The name of the region, such as a province or state, where the visitor is located. For example, Kansas.

columns.name: location_region_code
columns.description: The code for the region, such as a province or state, where the visitor is located. For example, KS.

columns.name: location_country
columns.description: The name of the country where the visitor is located. For example, United States.

columns.name: location_country_code
columns.description: The two-digit ISO country code where the visitor is located. For example, US.
